00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:07.990
by English language readers.

00:05:07.990 --> 00:05:13.330
The two of us have spent more
than 10 years, and many weekends

00:05:13.330 --> 00:05:17.230
around Ellen's dining room
table, immersed in the life

00:05:17.230 --> 00:05:19.720
and work of this unique writer.

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:22.680
And now, with the publication
of our translated collection

00:05:22.680 --> 00:05:26.950
of her short stories, we are
glad to have the opportunity

00:05:26.950 --> 00:05:29.590
to share our findings with you.

00:05:29.590 --> 00:05:33.410 position:56%
Today, we will take you on a kind
of mystery tour, to answer questions

00:05:33.410 --> 00:05:36.640
like these: where did
this writer come from?

00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:38.630
Who was she?

00:05:38.630 --> 00:05:41.890
What set her on her unusual path?

00:05:41.890 --> 00:05:44.770
What kept her going
through her long career?

00:05:44.770 --> 00:05:46.950
Why did she write in Yiddish?

00:05:46.950 --> 00:05:50.130
And what does she have to
offer a contemporary audience

00:05:50.130 --> 00:05:52.370
like ourselves?

00:05:52.370 --> 00:05:56.210
Blume Lempel was a unique
writer, one of a kind,

00:05:56.210 --> 00:05:58.590
but she was part of
a larger picture.

00:05:58.590 --> 00:06:01.700
So as we look at Blume
Lempel, we'll also be exploring

00:06:01.700 --> 00:06:06.090
that larger context of what it
was to be a writer in Yiddish

00:06:06.090 --> 00:06:08.620
in the second half
of the 20th Century

00:06:08.620 --> 00:06:11.730
in the United States,
and as a woman.

00:06:11.730 --> 00:06:16.440
But first, a word about how
we stumbled into this project,

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:19.740
and then we'll get into
Blume Lempel's story.

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:25.250
&gt;&gt; Ellen Cassedy: Years ago,
I began studying Yiddish

00:06:25.250 --> 00:06:26.960
as a memorial to my mother.

00:06:26.960 --> 00:06:29.860
My mother was Jewish,
unlike my father,

00:06:29.860 --> 00:06:32.530
and had grown up around Yiddish.

00:06:32.530 --> 00:06:35.920
She didn't actually speak Yiddish,
but she would sprinkle a word here,

00:06:35.920 --> 00:06:39.020
and a word there, into her
conversation sort of like a spice.

00:06:39.020 --> 00:06:41.080
So in the kitchen,
she might say "hand me

00:06:41.080 --> 00:06:45.520
that shissle [phonetic spelling]"
Does anyone know what that means?

00:06:45.520 --> 00:06:49.660
No? Bowl. Or she'd stand at the
window on a rainy day and say,

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:52.930
"Amabel [phonetic spelling]"
which meant "a flood."

00:06:52.930 --> 00:06:58.230
On the phone, the woman's [Yiddish
spoken], a witch [laughter].

00:06:58.230 --> 00:07:03.870
So I hope that by studying Yiddish,
I would strengthen my connection

00:07:03.870 --> 00:07:08.240
to my cultural legacy, and really
find a home within Jewish culture,

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:10.230
and that has turned out to be true.

00:07:10.230 --> 00:07:15.060
Yiddish is very precious to me,
for its outsider point of view,

00:07:15.060 --> 00:07:20.040
its humor, its standing up
for the little guy, its irony,

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:23.060
and its honoring of the everyday.

00:07:23.060 --> 00:07:26.480
So early on in my study of Yiddish,
I was living in Philadelphia,

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:29.760
and I told my teacher, who
was himself a translator,

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:32.140
that I wanted to try
my hand at translation.

00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:35.610 position:56%
At that time, I had about two months
of Yiddish study under my belt,

00:07:35.610 --> 00:07:37.180
I thought, "I'm ready for this."

00:07:37.180 --> 00:07:39.030
And he went straight
to his book shelf,

00:07:39.030 --> 00:07:41.880
and he pulled out this
little gray volume.

00:07:41.880 --> 00:07:46.490 position:56%
He opened it up, and he told me this
was by a writer named Blume Lempel,

00:07:46.490 --> 00:07:48.330
and he showed me how
it was inscribed

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:50.730
to him personally by the author.

00:07:50.730 --> 00:07:53.990
Then I met Ahron in a
Yiddish reading group.

00:07:53.990 --> 00:07:55.290
&gt;&gt; Yermiyahu Ahron Talb: I grew

00:07:55.290 --> 00:08:00.760
up in an Orthodox Shiva family
surrounded by Jewish languages,

00:08:00.760 --> 00:08:04.170
including Yiddish, and I formally
studied Yiddish as an adult.

00:08:04.170 --> 00:08:08.380
I've been involved in Yiddish
culture since the early 1990s.

00:08:08.380 --> 00:08:09.820
A long time now.

00:08:09.820 --> 00:08:14.590
As a reader, writer, translator and
activist, Yiddish is for me a place

00:08:14.590 --> 00:08:19.980
of primal connection, and
cultural imagining and possibility.

00:08:19.980 --> 00:08:23.300
&gt;&gt; Ellen Cassedy: So we opened up
this little gray volume and began

00:08:23.300 --> 00:08:30.360 position:56%
to read, and we were, frankly, blown
away by its truly unique writing.

00:08:30.360 --> 00:08:34.530
Experimental, taboo-defying,
fearless, lyrical.

00:08:34.530 --> 00:08:37.130
And there were surprises
at every turn.

00:08:37.130 --> 00:08:40.640
In on every page, in
virtually every paragraph,

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:44.950
we had never seen any writer
like this in any language.

00:08:44.950 --> 00:08:50.940
At the time, years ago, we knew
almost nothing about Blume Lempel,

00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:56.060
beyond the fact that she'd been
born in 1907, in Khorostkov,

00:08:56.060 --> 00:08:59.190
a little town in what
was then Galicia,

00:08:59.190 --> 00:09:03.420 position:56%
part of the Austro-Hungarian Empire,
later it became part of Poland,

00:09:03.420 --> 00:09:08.700
now it is in Ukraine, in what she
described as a whitewashed room

00:09:08.700 --> 00:09:12.100
by the banks of a river
that had no name.

00:09:12.100 --> 00:09:15.900
And we wondered who was this
woman who came out of this place,

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:19.930
who wrote with such feeling
and with so many exact details

00:09:19.930 --> 00:09:26.140 position:56%
about a very wide range of settings,
from the old world to the new,

00:09:26.140 --> 00:09:33.530 position:56%
pre-war Paris, Cosmopolitan Paris,
New York, California, Yosemite Park.

00:09:33.530 --> 00:09:37.350
How did somebody like her emerged
from a little whitewashed room

00:09:37.350 --> 00:09:39.990
to become such a groundbreaking
writer?

00:09:39.990 --> 00:09:44.070
So we went hunting, and we
tracked down Blume Lempel's heirs,

00:09:44.070 --> 00:09:47.790
her relatives, and her former
colleagues, and found boxes

00:09:47.790 --> 00:09:50.780
of her personal papers
stored in an attic.

00:09:50.780 --> 00:09:53.090
We came here to the
Library of Congress.

00:09:53.090 --> 00:09:57.120
We went to the Jewish Research
Institute called YIVO, in New York.

00:09:57.120 --> 00:10:00.060
And a picture began to emerge.

00:10:02.090 --> 00:10:03.690
&gt;&gt; Yermiyahu Ahron Talb: We
learned that Blume's father,

00:10:03.690 --> 00:10:09.070 position:56%
Abraham Pfeffer, was a butcher, and
that her mother, Pesha, read novels,

00:10:09.070 --> 00:10:14.330
subscribed to a newspaper from
the nearby city of Lvov, Lvov,

00:10:14.330 --> 00:10:17.880
and was considered
cultured by the townspeople.

00:10:17.880 --> 00:10:20.580
Blume's older brother
received a formal education,

00:10:20.580 --> 00:10:23.410
but her own schooling was sporadic.

00:10:23.410 --> 00:10:26.800
For a few years, she attended
a religious school for girls,

00:10:26.800 --> 00:10:32.540
and a Hebrew Folk School, and at
times, a tutor came to the house.

00:10:32.540 --> 00:10:35.780
As she later recalled in an
interview with the Yiddish scholar,

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:40.500
Itzel Gottesman, "My father
believed that all a girl needed

00:10:40.500 --> 00:10:47.710
to know was how to cook a pot of
food, sew a patch, and milk a cow."

00:10:47.710 --> 00:10:51.190
In Poland, she remembered,
"I didn't write at all.

00:10:51.190 --> 00:10:53.660
I only dreamed of writing."

00:10:53.660 --> 00:10:56.760
As she dreamed, she
stored up observations

00:10:56.760 --> 00:10:59.420 position:56%
that would later appear in her work.

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:03.700
All her life, her childhood
self remained accessible

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:06.690
to her as, "The girl who was.

00:11:06.690 --> 00:11:13.930
The girl whose tides ebb and flow
on my sandy shores, to this day."

00:11:13.930 --> 00:11:16.130
&gt;&gt; Ellen Cassedy: So, for a time,

00:11:16.130 --> 00:11:20.560
Blume Lempel's childhood
world seemed safe and secure.

00:11:20.560 --> 00:11:25.420
As the narrator in one story says,
"Enclosed within my father's words

00:11:25.420 --> 00:11:30.960
and my mother's tears, the world
came to me as a completed picture,

00:11:30.960 --> 00:11:34.530
and I accepted its
pre-ordained colors and nuances

00:11:34.530 --> 00:11:36.720
as part of the natural order.

00:11:36.720 --> 00:11:40.560
Just as the sun rose every
morning behind our barn,

00:11:40.560 --> 00:11:42.880
and set every evening
behind the tree

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:45.720
that my father pointed
out with his finger.

00:11:45.720 --> 00:11:49.870
So, I stayed within the picture
frame, walking in the light,

00:11:49.870 --> 00:11:54.090
avoiding the shadows, never
straying beyond the borders."

00:11:54.090 --> 00:11:57.380
And this is from a story called
Even the Heavens Tell Lies,

00:11:57.380 --> 00:11:58.680
[Yiddish words spoken].

00:11:58.680 --> 00:12:02.730
Now, would you like
to hear it in Yiddish?

00:12:02.730 --> 00:12:04.140
A little paragraph.

00:12:04.140 --> 00:12:07.140
And for those that don't know
Yiddish, remember the words

00:12:07.140 --> 00:12:11.310
of Franz Kafka, who said, "Ladies
and gentlemen, don't be afraid

00:12:11.310 --> 00:12:14.470
of Yiddish, you'll understand
more than you thought you would."

00:12:14.470 --> 00:12:17.440
So here is that paragraph,
in Yiddish.

00:12:18.510 --> 00:13:14.040
[ Yiddish Spoken ]

00:13:14.040 --> 00:13:16.370
&gt;&gt; Yermiyahu Ahron Talb: When
Blume was 12, that comforting sense

00:13:16.370 --> 00:13:18.740
of order began to crumble.

00:13:18.740 --> 00:13:23.720
Her mother died, and when her
father remarried, Blume was pressed

00:13:23.720 --> 00:13:27.360
into service as a housekeeper
and nursemaid

00:13:27.360 --> 00:13:30.210
for the new couple,
and their young child.

00:13:30.210 --> 00:13:34.890
Her brother, Yisroel, eight
years older, had become involved

00:13:34.890 --> 00:13:37.320
in militant communist activity.

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:44.110
He was caught and imprisoned, then
escaped, and went into hiding.

00:13:44.110 --> 00:13:49.530
Yisroel fled to France,
and in 1929, at age 22,

00:13:49.530 --> 00:13:52.170
Blume too left Khorostkov.

00:13:52.170 --> 00:13:57.950
She was intending to become
a pioneer in Palestine,

00:13:57.950 --> 00:14:01.900
but on the way, she stopped
off in Paris to visit Yisroel,

00:14:01.900 --> 00:14:06.650
who settled in the Jewish immigrant
neighborhood of Belleville.

00:14:06.650 --> 00:14:11.050
Captivated by the city of light,
Blume abandoned her pioneer plans.

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:16.170
She found a job in a factory, where
she met her husband Lemel Lempel.

00:14:16.170 --> 00:14:18.230
They started a family.

00:14:18.230 --> 00:14:21.510
Her dream of becoming a
writer began to take shape.

00:14:21.510 --> 00:14:25.240
She began writing poems, and
meeting other Yiddish writers.

00:14:25.240 --> 00:14:27.660
During the 10 years
Blume lived in Paris,

00:14:27.660 --> 00:14:29.540
she fell in love with the city.

00:14:29.540 --> 00:14:33.440
It became the setting for some
of her most important work,

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:36.470
including a novel set
in the years before

00:14:36.470 --> 00:14:40.990
and during World War II,
and many short stories.

00:14:42.650 --> 00:14:44.640
&gt;&gt; Ellen Cassedy: So,
just before World War II,

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:48.910
the family was extremely fortunate
to be able to flee to New York,

00:14:48.910 --> 00:14:54.570 position:56%
and here they are, a couple of years
after the war, the whole family.

00:14:54.570 --> 00:14:56.450
Those two children.

00:14:56.450 --> 00:15:01.400
And in America, Blume reached
out to the New York Jewish,

00:15:01.400 --> 00:15:05.910
Yiddish literary scene, especially
the newspaper Morgen Freiheit,

00:15:05.910 --> 00:15:11.010 position:56%
and she began to publish a
serialized novel, and short stories.

00:15:11.010 --> 00:15:15.170 position:56%
But then, the news from Europe
began to trickle in, and she learned

00:15:15.170 --> 00:15:19.150
that back in her hometown, her
father's wife, and their young son,

00:15:19.150 --> 00:15:22.270
had been seized and
killed by the Nazis,

00:15:22.270 --> 00:15:25.950
and that her father had
then burned down the house

00:15:25.950 --> 00:15:29.580
and hanged himself on
a tree in their yard.

00:15:29.580 --> 00:15:33.250
She also learned that on the
day before liberation of France,

00:15:33.250 --> 00:15:36.690
her brother, who had joined the
resistance, was captured and shot,

00:15:36.690 --> 00:15:39.530
leaving behind his
wife and two sons.

00:15:39.530 --> 00:15:44.390
As she later said, she was
catapulted into a deep despair.

00:15:44.390 --> 00:15:48.240
The past was a graveyard,
the future without meaning.

00:15:48.240 --> 00:15:52.500
I sat paralyzed within
a self-imposed prison.

00:15:52.500 --> 00:15:53.970
The years went by.

00:15:53.970 --> 00:15:57.830
Many desolate, fruitless years.

00:15:57.830 --> 00:16:00.620
She began to burn her work.

00:16:00.620 --> 00:16:02.260
But then came a turning point.

00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:06.030
She had two friends who were
Yiddish writers, and they suggested

00:16:06.030 --> 00:16:08.460 position:56%
that she dedicate herself to writing

00:16:08.460 --> 00:16:11.330
about the terrible destruction
that was consuming her.

00:16:11.330 --> 00:16:14.640
And that idea, she said,
opened a psychological door.

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:19.150
She wrote, "I felt I must speak for
those who could no longer speak.

00:16:19.150 --> 00:16:21.550
Feel for those who
could no longer feel.

00:16:21.550 --> 00:16:26.150
Immerse myself in their unlived
lives, their sorrows, their joys,

00:16:26.150 --> 00:16:28.170
their struggle and their death."

00:16:28.170 --> 00:16:32.640
So she had found her calling, which
was to express the experience of,

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:34.540
as she put it, "The survivors.

00:16:34.540 --> 00:16:39.200
The broken people who attempt after
the war to establish a new link

00:16:39.200 --> 00:16:41.880
to life, and who through
it all remain broken."

00:16:41.880 --> 00:16:43.980
And this was her own experience.

00:16:43.980 --> 00:16:48.070
An experience of displacement
and flight, and adaptation,

00:16:48.070 --> 00:16:54.260 position:56%
and a special burden of remembering,
retribution, guilt and grief.

00:16:54.260 --> 00:16:57.740
And in an approach that
was uniquely her own,

00:16:57.740 --> 00:17:02.210
she often approached her subject
not head-on, but through a variety

00:17:02.210 --> 00:17:06.340
of subtle literary strategies,
in which the great cataclysm

00:17:06.340 --> 00:17:10.170
of the 20th Century is
never far from the surface,

00:17:10.170 --> 00:17:12.320 position:56%
but it's hovering just out of sight,

00:17:12.320 --> 00:17:16.260
appearing in powerful
glimpses, powerful flashes.

00:17:16.260 --> 00:17:19.090
Many of her stories are
jagged and disjointed.

00:17:19.090 --> 00:17:22.850
They don't move smoothly from
point A to point B. Instead,

00:17:22.850 --> 00:17:25.340
sometimes within one
single sentence,

00:17:25.340 --> 00:17:29.940
you'll find Lempel's imagination
moving back and forth between dream

00:17:29.940 --> 00:17:33.510
and reality, past and
present, old world, and new.

00:17:33.510 --> 00:17:37.890 position:56%
And Ahron and I think that this
jaggedness is a carefully considered

00:17:37.890 --> 00:17:41.980
literary choice, one that is
unusual among Jewish writers.

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:45.670
We think it's a conscious
reflection of the disruptions

00:17:45.670 --> 00:17:49.200
in the author's life, and
the lives of her characters.

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:53.140
A brilliant, ingenious
way to convey the restless

00:17:53.140 --> 00:17:56.560
and unsettled existence
that she knew so well.

00:17:56.560 --> 00:18:00.470
&gt;&gt; Yermiyahu Ahron Talb:
So here is an example.

00:18:00.470 --> 00:18:04.060
In the story called The
Little Red Umbrella,

00:18:04.060 --> 00:18:08.470
a middle-aged woman named Janet,
in New York City, gets a phone call

00:18:08.470 --> 00:18:11.720
from a poet she met
at a Hanukah party.

00:18:11.720 --> 00:18:13.660
He invites her out on a date.

00:18:13.660 --> 00:18:16.800
He is one of a series of dates
she's had over the years.

00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:19.240
Most of them not that great.

00:18:19.240 --> 00:18:22.730
Including, as she tells
us, a washed-up actor,

00:18:22.730 --> 00:18:27.540
a sock manufacturer, a card-player,
a man who had left his wife

00:18:27.540 --> 00:18:31.850
and child to travel around
the world in disguise."

00:18:31.850 --> 00:18:33.300
So it doesn't look good.

00:18:33.300 --> 00:18:36.360
But this is a woman who
doesn't give up hope.

00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:40.790
And so listen to how,
within a single paragraph,

00:18:40.790 --> 00:18:47.320
Lempel catapults us out of Janet's
studio apartment, into the cosmos.

00:18:47.320 --> 00:18:52.400
The rendezvous with the poet came
like a jolt from the very heart

00:18:52.400 --> 00:18:58.190
of life, awakening the butterflies
from their lethargic dozing.

00:18:58.190 --> 00:19:01.870
Light, silk wings hovered
in the air.

00:19:01.870 --> 00:19:06.730 position:56%
The studio apartment, which a moment
before had been cold and dark,

00:19:06.730 --> 00:19:09.450
brightened with an ethereal light.

00:19:09.450 --> 00:19:12.360
The walls began to sing again.

00:19:12.360 --> 00:19:16.960
There's still life at close
to 50, she said to the fly

00:19:16.960 --> 00:19:19.910
that was spending the
winter in her house.

00:19:19.910 --> 00:19:25.810
Fantastic patterns streamed through
the cracks in the Venetian blinds.

00:19:25.810 --> 00:19:32.720 position:56%
Lost ships swarmed to her mountain,
bringing regards from distant lands.

00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:36.980
Magic keys to locked doors.

00:19:36.980 --> 00:19:40.590
Janet followed a voice
through the dark corridors.

00:19:40.590 --> 00:19:43.310
She opens one of the
doors, and inside,

00:19:43.310 --> 00:19:46.830
a purple light filled the room.

00:19:46.830 --> 00:19:54.290 position:56%
On a bed of sky-blue silk, the Greek
was lounging with a high-borne lady.

00:19:54.290 --> 00:19:58.740
Janet swims without moving
over still water, not forward,

00:19:58.740 --> 00:20:02.890
but backward in time,
from today to yesterday.

00:20:02.890 --> 00:20:05.560
The shift takes her
to the middle ages,

00:20:05.560 --> 00:20:09.100
to another world, on
another continent.

00:20:09.100 --> 00:20:14.520
She continues on to the land of
Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle.

00:20:14.520 --> 00:20:18.100
Then, to the promised
land of milk and honey.

00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:22.200
Under an outspread
fig tree, Adam dozes.

00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:23.500
She approaches him.

00:20:23.500 --> 00:20:28.490 position:56%
Then, the telephone rings, and Janet
goes to the closet, gets dressed,

00:20:28.490 --> 00:20:32.670
puts on her makeup and steps out
into the streets of Manhattan,

00:20:32.670 --> 00:20:35.490
on her way to the date
with the poet.

00:20:35.490 --> 00:20:37.920
The story goes on from
there, and once again,

00:20:37.920 --> 00:20:43.100
the Holocaust makes an
appearance in an unexpected way.

00:20:43.100 --> 00:20:44.520
Now, the erotic imaginings

00:20:44.520 --> 00:20:48.370
of a middle-aged woman are not
standard fare in any literature,

00:20:48.370 --> 00:20:52.670
and Lempel's approach to spooling
out this character's fantasies

00:20:52.670 --> 00:20:55.600
so freely is quite unusual.

00:20:55.600 --> 00:21:00.960
So, how did she summon the
courage to write this way?

00:21:03.950 --> 00:21:07.910
&gt;&gt; Ellen Cassedy: Perhaps the most
important factor was that by 1970,

00:21:07.910 --> 00:21:12.330
she had won the support of
Abraham Sutzkever, who was renowned

00:21:12.330 --> 00:21:17.200 position:56%
through the world of Yiddish letters
as a poet, as a cultural hero

00:21:17.200 --> 00:21:21.730
who had rescued treasured Jewish
texts in the Vilna ghetto,

00:21:21.730 --> 00:21:25.540
and as the editor of the leading
Yiddish literary journal called Di

00:21:25.540 --> 00:21:29.330
goldene keyt, which was
published in Tel Aviv.

00:21:29.330 --> 00:21:34.330
Sutzkever's right-hand man
was Alexander Spiegel-Vaught,

00:21:34.330 --> 00:21:36.190
and here is what the
Di goldene keyt,

00:21:36.190 --> 00:21:38.170
which means the golden
chain look like,

00:21:38.170 --> 00:21:41.850
and the golden chain means
the golden chain of Yiddish

00:21:41.850 --> 00:21:44.880
or Jewish literature that
is passed on from one writer

00:21:44.880 --> 00:21:47.170
to the next down through the ages.

00:21:47.170 --> 00:21:49.860
So after receiving her
first letter of acceptance

00:21:49.860 --> 00:21:53.310
from Di goldene keyt,
Lempel recalled this.

00:21:53.310 --> 00:21:57.520
"I still remember how surprised
I was at the warm answer.

00:21:57.520 --> 00:22:01.670
I remember even that it was a cold,
cloudy winter day, but for me,

00:22:01.670 --> 00:22:05.590
spring gardens burst into
the most beautiful bloom.

00:22:05.590 --> 00:22:11.810 position:56%
The energy that I'd conserved in my
youth came out from under my apron."

00:22:11.810 --> 00:22:15.230
Sutzkever and Lempel
corresponded for 20 years,

00:22:15.230 --> 00:22:17.730
and here we see an
early letter from him,

00:22:17.730 --> 00:22:21.720
complete with a rather charming
drawing, a portrait, self-portrait,

00:22:21.720 --> 00:22:25.230
signed, "All the best,
with love, Sutzkever."

00:22:25.230 --> 00:22:28.610
And while another editor might
have tried to reign her in,

00:22:28.610 --> 00:22:32.460
to smooth out her rough edges,
or tame her bold choices,

00:22:32.460 --> 00:22:34.780
what was critically
important about this editor,

00:22:34.780 --> 00:22:37.610
Abraham Sutzkever,
was that he never did.

00:22:37.610 --> 00:22:40.870
Instead, he deeply
affirmed her individuality.

00:22:40.870 --> 00:22:44.350
He wrote, "You have your own
words, your own observations,

00:22:44.350 --> 00:22:48.530
your own madness, which you
scoop out from within yourself

00:22:48.530 --> 00:22:51.200
like shovelfuls of hot coals.

00:22:51.200 --> 00:22:53.520
Your talent is not an ordinary one.

00:22:53.520 --> 00:22:55.720
Of that I am sure."

00:22:55.720 --> 00:22:58.390
So Sutzkever allowed
Lempel free reign

00:22:58.390 --> 00:23:02.050
to pursue her unique
narrative strategies, and this,

00:23:02.050 --> 00:23:06.560 position:56%
like the earlier intervention of
Lempel's few Yiddish writer friends,

00:23:06.560 --> 00:23:08.820
was a key factor in the development

00:23:08.820 --> 00:23:12.360
of her singular contribution
to Yiddish literature.

00:23:12.360 --> 00:23:14.500
Lempel wrote back to Sutzkever,

00:23:14.500 --> 00:23:17.680
"I write not for my
readers, but for myself.

00:23:17.680 --> 00:23:19.440
I write for the dybbuk

00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:21.860
that is seeking a transformation
through me."

00:23:21.860 --> 00:23:28.010
Now in Jewish folk culture, a
dybbuk is the soul of a dead person

00:23:28.010 --> 00:23:31.990
that takes up residence inside
a living individual and strives

00:23:31.990 --> 00:23:36.150
for expression through that
person, and Sutzkever wrote back,

00:23:36.150 --> 00:23:38.300
"for that dibbick you must write.

00:23:38.300 --> 00:23:40.740
You must write for
yourself, and for me,

00:23:40.740 --> 00:23:45.680
and for that chosen writer whom
every true talent brings into being

00:23:45.680 --> 00:23:48.070
through the magnetic
power of the work itself.

00:23:48.070 --> 00:23:50.580
Now, I think this is a
very interesting concept,

00:23:50.580 --> 00:23:54.960
that the writer kind of creates
an ideal reader inside his

00:23:54.960 --> 00:23:59.720
or her own head, and that reader is
the one that the writer writes for.

00:23:59.720 --> 00:24:03.450
"Your prose," Sutzkever said, "is
in essence poetic, and therefore,

00:24:03.450 --> 00:24:06.650
it must be pure and
careful, like pure poetry.

00:24:06.650 --> 00:24:10.690
Every drop is as important
as the rushing current.

00:24:10.690 --> 00:24:19.890
Sincerely, and with
much belief in you."

00:24:19.890 --> 00:24:22.510
&gt;&gt; Yermiyahu Ahron Talb:

00:24:22.510 --> 00:24:26.970 position:56%
Another important sustaining force
was the poet, Malka Heifetz Tussman,

00:24:26.970 --> 00:24:31.640
and here we see a photo
of her with her husband,

00:24:31.640 --> 00:24:34.340
both in bathing suits, no less.

00:24:34.340 --> 00:24:39.340
And here is a letter, here is a
letter from her, in which she talks

00:24:39.340 --> 00:24:44.660 position:56%
about the complex and very personal
literary home that Lempel had built.

00:24:44.660 --> 00:24:49.470 position:56%
She writes, "Blume, Blume, why do
you think your poems would shock me?

00:24:49.470 --> 00:24:52.840
Not so. Good poems, Blume.

00:24:52.840 --> 00:24:56.900
You dive into the self,
and behold, a sbibh."

00:24:56.900 --> 00:25:01.290
Here is Blume, and you can see
even the letter itself is written

00:25:01.290 --> 00:25:03.980
as a poem.

00:25:03.980 --> 00:25:08.440
In Yiddish, the word sbibh means
"environment" or "atmosphere."

00:25:08.440 --> 00:25:12.010
But it can also note
fellowship and connection.

00:25:12.010 --> 00:25:13.870
It is a place where one belongs.

00:25:13.870 --> 00:25:18.520
A home. The sbibh that Blume
Lempel constructed for herself,

00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:23.270
the sustaining literary home,
was part privacy and solitude,

00:25:23.270 --> 00:25:25.780
part support and community.

00:25:25.780 --> 00:25:29.110
As writers ourselves, we are
fascinated by Blume's sbibh,

00:25:29.110 --> 00:25:33.360
and how richly rewarding
it clearly was for her.

00:25:33.360 --> 00:25:37.960
In Heifetz Tussman's words,
"Blume is her own sbibh."

00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:42.870
And that is an important part
of the truth, but only one part.

00:25:42.870 --> 00:25:45.270
The support of other
writers was also a key part

00:25:45.270 --> 00:25:47.880
of what sustained her.

00:25:47.880 --> 00:25:51.650
Lempel's work became known
in the Yiddish world.

00:25:51.650 --> 00:25:54.750
As we were able to see in the
holdings here at the Library

00:25:54.750 --> 00:25:58.680
of Congress, it was published in a
great variety of Yiddish journals,

00:25:58.680 --> 00:26:02.210
in Tel Aviv, New York,
Los Angeles, Melbourne,

00:26:02.210 --> 00:26:05.890
Australia, Paris, and South Africa.

00:26:05.890 --> 00:26:08.050
She won several literary prizes,

00:26:08.050 --> 00:26:09.880
including the EKUF
[phonetic spelling] prize,

00:26:09.880 --> 00:26:13.060
the I.J. Seigel Prize, awarded
by the Jewish Public Library

00:26:13.060 --> 00:26:17.430
in Montreal, and the Haim
Shetovk [assumed spelling] Prize.

00:26:17.430 --> 00:26:21.370
&gt;&gt; Ellen Cassedy: In
1979, she began preparing

00:26:21.370 --> 00:26:24.940
for her first short story
collection to publish it,

00:26:24.940 --> 00:26:26.760
and for editorial help, she turned

00:26:26.760 --> 00:26:30.220
to this Tel Aviv poet named
Denham Heller [phonetic spelling]

00:26:30.220 --> 00:26:34.000
and he urged her to include
even her most daring stories,

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:36.530
ones that had been rejected
by literary magazines,

00:26:36.530 --> 00:26:38.840
including Oedipus in Brooklyn,

00:26:38.840 --> 00:26:41.440
the story that Sutzkever
himself has turned down.

00:26:41.440 --> 00:26:46.640 position:56%
And the result was this book, A
Moment Fun Ams, "a moment of truth,"

00:26:46.640 --> 00:26:51.680
the volume that my teacher
put in my hand 10 years later,

00:26:51.680 --> 00:26:55.120
and once the book was published,
praise began to pour in.

00:26:55.120 --> 00:26:59.220 position:56%
Praise that recognized that hers was
a unique voice, a talent distinct

00:26:59.220 --> 00:27:02.960
from others in the
Yiddish literary world.

00:27:02.960 --> 00:27:06.620
The writer, the celebrated
Yiddish writer, Chaim Grade,

00:27:06.620 --> 00:27:10.670
wrote to her how sad it was that
her talent had flowered so late,

00:27:10.670 --> 00:27:14.550 position:56%
when there were so few readers who
could read her work in the original,

00:27:14.550 --> 00:27:17.860
but he said maybe this was
inevitable, because she belonged

00:27:17.860 --> 00:27:20.910
so much to her own
time, and no other time.

00:27:20.910 --> 00:27:22.250
So listen to what he says.

00:27:22.250 --> 00:27:25.860
"It is enough to make one weep
that you appeared in our literature

00:27:25.860 --> 00:27:29.430
at a time when so few
good readers remained,

00:27:29.430 --> 00:27:32.110
but perhaps it could
not have been otherwise.

00:27:32.110 --> 00:27:36.390
Perhaps your magical, sweet,
lyrical tone could not have come

00:27:36.390 --> 00:27:40.370
into being any earlier
than our autumn years.

00:27:40.370 --> 00:27:45.100
You are a modern writer in
the most beautiful sense.

00:27:49.810 --> 00:27:51.890
&gt;&gt; Yermiyahu Ahron Talb: Lempel
also attracted the attention

00:27:51.890 --> 00:27:54.820
of the Montreal writer, Java
Rosenfarb [phonetic spelling],

00:27:54.820 --> 00:27:58.240
who introduced herself
to Lempel in a letter.

00:27:58.240 --> 00:28:01.910
"I've been reading your work
in Di goldene keyt," she wrote.

00:28:01.910 --> 00:28:05.910
"I feel very close to your
way of writing, to your style.

00:28:05.910 --> 00:28:07.740
Who are you?"

00:28:07.740 --> 00:28:12.220
The two women exchanged warm
and frequent letters until 1990,

00:28:12.220 --> 00:28:15.300
critiquing each other's work,
revealing their struggles

00:28:15.300 --> 00:28:20.060 position:56%
with writing and publishing, sharing
their views of other writers,

00:28:20.060 --> 00:28:21.980
some of which are not so positive,

00:28:21.980 --> 00:28:24.360
and offering news about
their families.

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:27.450
Rosenfarb wrote, "I
admire the beauty

00:28:27.450 --> 00:28:29.640
and austerity of your language.

00:28:29.640 --> 00:28:36.120
You are so economical, careful
not to waste a single word."

00:28:36.120 --> 00:28:41.420
We agree. As translators, we found
her prose so poetic and so rich

00:28:41.420 --> 00:28:45.600
that we had to work very hard
to capture her unique melody,

00:28:45.600 --> 00:28:51.810 position:56%
one that we found to be denser, more
idiosyncratic, more well...unhinged,

00:28:51.810 --> 00:28:56.820
than that of other women
or men writing in Yiddish.

00:28:56.820 --> 00:29:01.020
That one...

00:29:01.020 --> 00:29:02.700
&gt;&gt; Ellen Cassedy: Perfect, perfect.

00:29:02.700 --> 00:29:05.580
&gt;&gt; Yermiyahu Ahron Talb: Lempel's
second collection came out in 1986,

00:29:05.580 --> 00:29:10.180
and was called "Balade fun a
kholem," ballad of a dream.

00:29:10.180 --> 00:29:12.980
Like her first book, it
contains an extraordinary range

00:29:12.980 --> 00:29:14.600
of subject matter.

00:29:14.600 --> 00:29:18.150
In her stories, we meet
women and girls of all ages.

00:29:18.150 --> 00:29:22.310 position:56%
A lonely little girl who is too
poor to own a doll, so she draws one

00:29:22.310 --> 00:29:24.740
with her finger on
a misty windowpane.

00:29:24.740 --> 00:29:28.040
A madwoman dancing
in the marketplace.

00:29:28.040 --> 00:29:30.190
A mother and son living
in the forest

00:29:30.190 --> 00:29:33.260
with the squirrels to
hide from the Nazis.

00:29:33.260 --> 00:29:38.170
A woman lying on her back on a
table, in an abortion clinic.

00:29:38.170 --> 00:29:42.740
A woman who occupies herself
with extravagant daydreams,

00:29:42.740 --> 00:29:46.880
as she and her husband drive
to Florida for the winter.

00:29:46.880 --> 00:29:53.560 position:56%
An anti-Nazi spy in Paris, disguised
behind a mask of glamorous makeup.

00:29:53.560 --> 00:29:57.030
A deeply religious African
American woman living in Brooklyn.

00:29:57.030 --> 00:30:00.050
A woman named Pakasandra [phonetic
spelling], who tells a lie

00:30:00.050 --> 00:30:03.770
to save her son's life, and
then is obsessed with the fear

00:30:03.770 --> 00:30:08.370
that God will punish her for the
sin of bearing false witness.

00:30:08.370 --> 00:30:13.160
In response to the second volume,
Yunya Fein [phonetic spelling],

00:30:13.160 --> 00:30:17.440
a Yiddish writer, an artist who
lived in New York, wrote to Lempel.

00:30:17.440 --> 00:30:22.620
And we think this is a really
nice synthesis of her writing.

00:30:22.620 --> 00:30:27.150
Yunya wrote, "Throughout
your stories, time undulates.

00:30:27.150 --> 00:30:31.780
Not measured or divided into
past, present and future.

00:30:31.780 --> 00:30:36.850
As long as we are alive, we carry
all times within us simultaneously.

00:30:36.850 --> 00:30:41.050
And who knows for sure what
is fact and what is dream?

00:30:41.050 --> 00:30:46.570 position:56%
And who can say with certainty how
much arrival there is in going away?

00:30:46.570 --> 00:30:51.370 position:56%
And how much going away in arriving?

00:30:51.370 --> 00:30:54.620
These and many other
questions are woven

00:30:54.620 --> 00:30:58.030
in a natural way into your work."

00:30:58.030 --> 00:31:01.470
For example, the aforementioned
Pakasandra,

00:31:01.470 --> 00:31:05.680
the woman who told a lie, lives
with the images of Biblical figures

00:31:05.680 --> 00:31:08.720
in her mind, all day, every day.

00:31:08.720 --> 00:31:11.660
Here is a brief excerpt.

00:31:11.660 --> 00:31:15.540
"All day, while her mind
was busy with this and that,

00:31:15.540 --> 00:31:17.640
the images were in motion.

00:31:17.640 --> 00:31:21.840
She saw Abraham's caravan
on the edge of the desert,

00:31:21.840 --> 00:31:27.280
and the matriarch, Sarah, encircled
by a retinue of maidservants.

00:31:27.280 --> 00:31:33.310
And wrapped in white linen, riding
side saddle on a small donkey.

00:31:33.310 --> 00:31:39.080
Pakasandra couldn't see her face,
but sensed her royal bearing.

00:31:39.080 --> 00:31:44.090
And with the utmost respect, she
chose not to peel away the swaths

00:31:44.090 --> 00:31:47.480
of fabric protecting her privacy.

00:31:47.480 --> 00:31:52.140
The images populated Pakasandra's
world, which she tended

00:31:52.140 --> 00:31:54.890
in a special chamber of her being.

00:31:54.890 --> 00:31:59.130
Minute as a pinhead,
and yet, infinite."

00:32:00.150 --> 00:32:02.690
&gt;&gt; Ellen Cassedy: And now, a word,
for what you've been waiting for,

00:32:02.690 --> 00:32:05.400
about the title story,
Oedipus in Brooklyn.

00:32:05.400 --> 00:32:06.700
What is this?

00:32:06.700 --> 00:32:09.510
This was a story that Sutzkever
considered too shocking

00:32:09.510 --> 00:32:11.560
to publish and maybe he was right.

00:32:11.560 --> 00:32:13.180
You can be the judge.

00:32:13.180 --> 00:32:16.020
But we find that in Lempel's hands,

00:32:16.020 --> 00:32:19.220
the account of a contemporary
woman involved

00:32:19.220 --> 00:32:23.590
in a transgressive relationship
with her son is not sensational,

00:32:23.590 --> 00:32:26.470
not tawdry, and not
played for laughs.

00:32:26.470 --> 00:32:30.520
Step by step, Lempel leads us
into the heart of darkness.

00:32:30.520 --> 00:32:33.580
She tells about the car
accident that kills the father

00:32:33.580 --> 00:32:37.690
and blinds the son, of the growing
closeness of mother and son,

00:32:37.690 --> 00:32:39.800
and of their increasing isolation.

00:32:39.800 --> 00:32:43.640
And finally, the two of them leave
the familiar streets of Brooklyn,

00:32:43.640 --> 00:32:47.750
and move to Florida, which becomes
a perfect backdrop of horror

00:32:47.750 --> 00:32:50.260
for the tragedy that
is beginning to unfold.

00:32:50.260 --> 00:32:51.730
Here is her description of Florida.

00:32:51.730 --> 00:32:57.330
"A blinding haze hung in
the air like carbon fumes.

00:32:57.330 --> 00:33:00.980
The earth was scorched,
the waterways dried up,

00:33:00.980 --> 00:33:03.350
the white Egrets disappeared.

00:33:03.350 --> 00:33:08.960
Creeping insects of all kinds
eked out their slithery existence,

00:33:08.960 --> 00:33:14.880
leaving behind silver threads of
slime on the desiccated water bed.

00:33:14.880 --> 00:33:18.270
Sylvia and Danny hid from the sun.

00:33:18.270 --> 00:33:23.590
In the house, the air conditioner
cooled their parched bodies."

00:33:23.590 --> 00:33:27.140
So, by the end of the story,
we've come to understand something

00:33:27.140 --> 00:33:32.530
about both the mother and the son,
and perhaps, even to sympathize.

00:33:32.530 --> 00:33:37.690
There's the picture of what
her second volume looked like.

00:33:37.690 --> 00:33:41.110
And here she is near
the end of her life.

00:33:42.840 --> 00:33:45.130
&gt;&gt; Yermiyahu Ahron Talb: Finally,
why did Blume Lempel write

00:33:45.130 --> 00:33:47.680
in Yiddish, and keep
writing in Yiddish,

00:33:47.680 --> 00:33:52.380
even as the Yiddish readership grew
smaller and smaller year by year?

00:33:52.380 --> 00:33:55.540
She wrote, "Yiddish is in my bones.

00:33:55.540 --> 00:33:58.330
I hear my mother's [Yiddish
word spoken] in my head,

00:33:58.330 --> 00:34:00.870
and I lift my eyes to the heavens,

00:34:00.870 --> 00:34:03.540
and hear God answering
me in Yiddish.

00:34:03.540 --> 00:34:06.990
The birds, real and
imagined, speak Yiddish.

00:34:06.990 --> 00:34:09.950
And the wind at my
window speaks Yiddish,

00:34:09.950 --> 00:34:13.270
because I speak Yiddish,
think in Yiddish.

00:34:13.270 --> 00:34:15.690
So Yiddish was a portable homeland.

00:34:15.690 --> 00:34:19.380
A way of remaining true to
a world that was no more,

00:34:19.380 --> 00:34:21.560
while she made her
way to new places,

00:34:21.560 --> 00:34:25.500
confronting new circumstances,
in new languages.

00:34:26.780 --> 00:34:29.740
Yiddish was also a way to honor
the six million who perished

00:34:29.740 --> 00:34:33.620
in the Holocaust, including
the members of her own family.

00:34:33.620 --> 00:34:38.260
She wrote, "My older brother
tells me what to write in Yiddish,

00:34:38.260 --> 00:34:41.650
directing my stories
from beyond the grave.

00:34:41.650 --> 00:34:43.310
This is how it was.

00:34:43.310 --> 00:34:44.740
This is what happened.

00:34:44.740 --> 00:34:47.240
So must it be recorded.

00:34:47.240 --> 00:34:52.730
You did not survive simply to
eat blintzes with sour cream.

00:34:52.730 --> 00:34:55.880
You survived to bring back
those who were annihilated.

00:34:55.880 --> 00:35:00.210
You must speak in their
tongue, point their fingers."

00:35:00.210 --> 00:35:04.160
And for Lempel, Yiddish
was also a way to hide.

00:35:04.160 --> 00:35:06.520
Writing in Yiddish
could feel isolating.

00:35:06.520 --> 00:35:11.080
But we think maybe that
very isolation freed Lempel

00:35:11.080 --> 00:35:15.210
to pursue her own idiosyncratic
vision.

00:35:15.210 --> 00:35:18.410
Even as she was being published
in Yiddish periodicals,

00:35:18.410 --> 00:35:22.010
receiving literary prizes,
and corresponding in Yiddish

00:35:22.010 --> 00:35:27.560
with readers and writers all over
the world, living in her sbibh.

00:35:27.560 --> 00:35:31.180
At the same time, her children
couldn't read what she wrote,

00:35:31.180 --> 00:35:33.470
and her neighbors in
Long Beach, New York,

00:35:33.470 --> 00:35:37.570
had no idea she was a
world published writer.

00:35:37.570 --> 00:35:40.130
She told Itzel Gottesman this.

00:35:40.130 --> 00:35:43.740
"I hide my literary
existence under my apron.

00:35:43.740 --> 00:35:46.310
If you ask my neighbors
about my writing,

00:35:46.310 --> 00:35:48.260
they'd think you were crazy."

00:35:48.260 --> 00:35:52.020
So perhaps writing in Yiddish in
an English-speaking world helped

00:35:52.020 --> 00:35:56.890
to liberate Lempel to be the
taboo-defying writer she was meant

00:35:56.890 --> 00:35:58.320
to be.

00:35:58.320 --> 00:36:02.970
&gt;&gt; Ellen Cassedy: When Blume died
in 1999, at her home in Long Beach,

00:36:02.970 --> 00:36:07.830
Long Island, an article in the
[inaudible], the Yiddish newspaper

00:36:07.830 --> 00:36:11.230
in New York stated, "With
the passing of Blume Lempel,

00:36:11.230 --> 00:36:14.980
Yiddish literature has lost one
of its most remarkable writers.

00:36:14.980 --> 00:36:17.820
An empty spot has opened
in the galaxy

00:36:17.820 --> 00:36:21.030
of talented women Yiddish writers."

00:36:21.030 --> 00:36:25.610
So, in closing, we want to read
to you a luminous passage from one

00:36:25.610 --> 00:36:28.480
of Lempel's most extraordinary
stories called Waiting

00:36:28.480 --> 00:36:29.780
for the Ragman.

00:36:29.780 --> 00:36:33.920
And it is about her girlhood in
the little town in Eastern Europe,

00:36:33.920 --> 00:36:37.810 position:56%
and about how her memories have come
with her, have traveled with her

00:36:37.810 --> 00:36:41.020 position:56%
into adulthood, and this time, I'm
going to read you the Yiddish first,

00:36:41.020 --> 00:36:43.510
and see how much you can get.

00:36:43.510 --> 00:37:19.040
[ Yiddish Being Spoken ]

00:37:19.040 --> 00:37:20.340
&gt;&gt; Ellen Cassedy: And
now in English,

00:37:20.340 --> 00:37:24.820
"The young Passover son liked
to play with the colored glasses

00:37:24.820 --> 00:37:28.540
that stood on the sideboard
in honor of the holiday.

00:37:28.540 --> 00:37:32.360
The son poured the colors
together and transmuted them

00:37:32.360 --> 00:37:37.420
into shimmering stars that
spangled the whitewashed walls,

00:37:37.420 --> 00:37:41.220
the clay floor, and the table
with its Seder plate set

00:37:41.220 --> 00:37:43.770
in the middle of the snowy cloth.

00:37:43.770 --> 00:37:49.390
As I lifted my hands in the air,
the beams rained down over my head,

00:37:49.390 --> 00:37:54.330
like a golden raisin wine that
began to ferment inside me.

00:37:54.330 --> 00:37:58.750
To this day, I capture
handfuls of sunbeams,

00:37:58.750 --> 00:38:02.780
and use them to illuminate
the shadows."

00:38:07.330 --> 00:38:10.290
&gt;&gt; Yermiyahu Ahron Talb: During
her lifetime, Lempel's dream

00:38:10.290 --> 00:38:15.170
of an English language readership
for the most part eluded her.

00:38:15.170 --> 00:38:19.750
It is a joy for us now to help
her unrealized dream come true.

00:38:19.750 --> 00:38:23.860
As we bring Blume's shimmering
sunbeams, and her abundant shadows

00:38:23.860 --> 00:38:28.090
to new readers like you, we hope
we're helping this great writer

00:38:28.090 --> 00:38:30.510
to be known as she
wanted to be known,

00:38:30.510 --> 00:38:33.500
as a bold explorer of new terrain.

00:38:33.500 --> 00:38:37.470
As a dazzling stylist, and as
a profound teller of truths

00:38:37.470 --> 00:38:39.380
about the human condition.

00:38:39.380 --> 00:38:43.240
As new generations of readers
encounter Lempel's work,

00:38:43.240 --> 00:38:45.780
whether in the original
Yiddish, or in translation,

00:38:45.780 --> 00:38:49.450
they will have the opportunity
to step into her sbibh.

00:38:49.450 --> 00:38:52.680
As they do, they'll
be richly rewarded.

00:38:52.680 --> 00:38:56.080
We hope you'll enjoy her
work, savor it, learn from it,

00:38:56.080 --> 00:38:57.840
and share it with others.

00:38:57.840 --> 00:39:02.510
So, again, thank you all for
coming, and [Yiddish being spoken].

